# Purpose

Structured checklist for reviewing pull requests to enforce architecture, security, testing, and code quality standards.

# Workflow

## 1. Verify Conventional Commit Messages

- All commit messages MUST follow `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, `test:`, `docs:` prefixes.
- Enforced by commitlint + husky. If missing, request correction before merge.

## 2. Check Architecture Boundaries

- Backend: `modules/` MUST NOT import from other `modules/`.
- Frontend: `pages/` MUST NOT import from `ui/` directly — only via `ui-app/` wrappers.
- Frontend: `store/` slices MUST NOT contain API calls.
- Generated files (`_gen/`, `ui/`) MUST NOT be manually edited.

## 3. Validate Typing and Validation

- No `any` types introduced.
- API request types derived from Zod schemas, not written manually.
- All MongoDB documents validated with `parseSchema` on read.
- Frontend payload types come from `_gen/` (Orval), not manual interfaces.

## 4. Review Security

- No secrets or `.env` files committed.
- New routes that access user data MUST have `authenticateContextMiddleware`.
- Passwords hashed with bcrypt. No plain-text storage or logging.
- Refresh token set only as `httpOnly` cookie — not in response body.
- Rate limiters present on new auth-adjacent routes.

## 5. Review Error Handling

- Backend errors thrown as typed exceptions (`aop/exceptions`), not manual `res.status().json()`.
- Transaction blocks have `abortTransaction` in catch and `endSession` in finally.
- Frontend catches `CustomError`, logs via `logging.error`, and does not swallow errors.

## 6. Review Tests

- Integration tests present for new/modified endpoints.
- Tests assert HTTP contract (status, `body.success`, response shape).
- `beforeEach` clears collections in integration tests.
- No `test.only` or `it.skip` in committed code.

## 7. Run Validation Commands

```bash
# Backend
cd backend && npm run type-check && npm run lint && npm test && npm run test:integration

# Frontend
cd frontend && npm run type-check && npm run lint
```

## 8. Verify Response Shape Consistency

All successful responses follow:

```json
{ "success": true, "data": <payload> }
```

Paginated:

```json
{ "success": true, "data": [], "limit": 0, "offset": 0, "count": 0 }
```

Error (from `exceptionsMiddleware`):

```json
{ "success": false, "issues": [], "code": "ERROR_TYPE", "timestamp": "ISO string" }
```

## Completion Criteria

- [ ] Commit messages follow Conventional Commits
- [ ] Architecture boundaries respected
- [ ] No `any` types or manual API type definitions
- [ ] Security constraints satisfied
- [ ] Typed exceptions used for all error paths
- [ ] Integration tests added/updated
- [ ] `type-check` and `lint` pass in both packages
- [ ] Response shapes consistent with existing API contract
